For instance, the major natural resource in the area has been channelled to Nairobi by construction of Ndakaini Dam three decades ago. Instead of allowing residents to use the remaining water, another project code named Northern Water Collector Tunnel harvests water from streams and rivers and delivers it by pipe to Nairobi.
The dual carriageway from Kenol was mooted to pass through Murang’a town and would have brought economic tidings to Kaharati and Maragua, but was diverted. Coffee, tea and avocados attracts meagre prices while the cost of production is very high due to lack of subsidies.





Unemployment rates
In his letter, Senator Kang’ata reiterated that “jeshi ti ngenu” due to marginalisation that began during the Moi era. Unemployment is rife while young men are labelled as members of a sect. The Majority Leader in Parliament Amos Kimunya insinuated that the senator only spoke to people whose pre-occupation is to hang around in shopping centres (Mung’etho).
Murang’a is a shell of its former self with vibrant towns growing cold and dangerous. Once-prosperous towns, such as Maragua, Kiriani, Kirwara, Kangema, Kahuro, Gatura, Kangari, Kandara, Muthithi and Kaharati, are almost dead.
Kang’ata only fell short of asking politicians to draft bills in Parliament to address coffee, tea, avocado, bananas, milk and horticultural products. The Sh15 billion stimulus package for fish farming excluded Murang’a to cover only Embu, Kirirnyaga and Nyeri, yet it has more water.



